## .NET 8 Migration: `EventProcessor`

### Critical Issues in the Original Code

| Issue | Severity | Details |
|-------|----------|---------|
| `Thread.Abort()` | 💥 **Throws at runtime** | `PlatformNotSupportedException` in .NET 6+ |
| `Thread.Interrupt()` | ⚠️ **Obsolete** | `SYSLIB0006` — no-ops or throws depending on state |
| Race condition | 🐛 **Bug** | Multiple `Enqueue` calls between `WaitOne`/`Reset` lose items |
| No graceful shutdown | 🐛 **Bug** | No cancellation signal — loop runs `while(true)` forever |

### Migrated Code

```csharp
using System.Threading.Channels;

public class EventProcessor : IAsyncDisposable
{
    private readonly Channel<string> _channel = Channel.CreateUnbounded<string>();
    private Task? _processTask;
    private CancellationTokenSource? _cts;

    public void Start()
    {
        _cts = new CancellationTokenSource();
        _processTask = Task.Run(() => RunLoopAsync(_cts.Token));
    }

    private async Task RunLoopAsync(CancellationToken ct)
    {
        try
        {
            await foreach (var item in _channel.Reader.ReadAllAsync(ct))
            {
                Handle(item);
            }
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) { }
    }

    public void Enqueue(string item)
    {
        if (!_channel.Writer.TryWrite(item))
            throw new InvalidOperationException("Channel closed.");
    }

    public async ValueTask Stop()
    {
        _channel.Writer.Complete();          // signal no more items
        _cts?.CancelAfter(TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5)); // hard deadline

        if (_processTask is not null)
            await _processTask;

        _cts?.Dispose();
    }

    public async ValueTask DisposeAsync()
    {
        await Stop();
        GC.SuppressFinalize(this);
    }

    private void Handle(string item) { /* your logic */ }
}
```

### What Changed and Why

**`Channel<T>` replaces `ManualResetEvent` + `Queue` + `lock`**
— Thread-safe producer/consumer with built-in backpressure. Eliminates the race condition where multiple enqueues between `WaitOne`/`Reset` caused lost items.

**`CancellationToken` replaces `Thread.Abort`/`Interrupt`**
— Cooperative cancellation is the only supported pattern in modern .NET. `ReadAllAsync(ct)` exits cleanly on cancellation.

**`Task.Run` replaces `new Thread`**
— Uses the thread pool instead of a dedicated thread. If you need a long-lived dedicated thread, use `Task.Factory.StartNew(..., TaskCreationOptions.LongRunning)`.

**Two-phase shutdown: graceful then forced**
— `Writer.Complete()` drains remaining items; `CancelAfter(5s)` acts as the hard timeout, replacing the old `Join(5000)` + `Abort()` pattern.

### Pitfall Checklist

- ❌ Don't search-replace `Abort()` with `Environment.FailFast` — that kills the process
- ❌ Don't use `Thread.Interrupt()` — it's a no-op on `Channel` waits and obsolete
- ⚠️ If `Handle()` is CPU-heavy, consider `LongRunning` or a dedicated thread
- ⚠️ If `Handle()` calls async APIs, make it `async Task HandleAsync()` and `await` it
- ✅ `Channel.CreateBounded<T>(capacity)` if you need backpressure on producers
